<p>The Trinity Study helped popularize the idea that a diversified portfolio could historically support withdrawals near 4% over long periods. But that research was often simplified into false certainty. The 1970s inflation shock showed why nominal returns can mislead: a portfolio may rise in dollars while losing real purchasing power. The 2000–2009 lost decade showed why beginners should not assume smooth equity returns. And 2008 made sequence risk painfully clear: someone still working and buying index funds through the crash could recover well, while someone retiring into that decline with no cash buffer or flexibility faced a much harder path.</p>
